---
title: 'Don''t get used to Skills, they''ll (mostly) be gone in a year.'
description: 'Why Skills don''t pass first principles '
tags:
  - Skills
  - agents
date: '2026-04-07'
---
I predict that in a year or so, the way people interact and think about Skills will be vastly different, in that we will barely know or think about them. Skills are the latest buzz in the world of AI trend catchers, preceded by prompt libraries and multi-agents. They solve a really important problem, which is progressive disclosure of know how. However, just like their predecessors, they fail some basic first principles in the long run. Take prompt libraries, or GPTs as they used to be called, why did they fail? No one wants to write prompts, let alone maintain and improve them. We just want the agent we are talking to do the thing we want it to do, the way we want it to do it (preferably even better than what we imagine). Who wants to write an agent and think about how it should be only written for situations where either the process can run in parallel or if the output from it will be more valuable than how it got to the output? I just want the agent I am talking to, to do the task I give it as quickly and as thoroughly as possible. 

Skills solve a real problem, letting agents dynamically load context based on the task at hand. But first principles wise they don't hold up long term. They are used for a handful of categories. Sometimes they are a cache for anything an agent can get to if it did some research online, sometimes they hold users preferences on how they would like the agent to act, most valuably they can also capture some repeatable proprietary information or workflow. However, they suffer the same problem as prompt libraries, no one actually wants to create and upkeep Skills and they shouldn't have to. Most of the above use cases will be eaten by agents with better, more proactive memory systems, newer models, and agents that will focus on learning through questions first instead of trying to one shot every prompt. Many Skills of opinionated workflows and knowledge caches will likely move to a central repository with a layer that automagically searches and recommends or even injects them into context based on the task at hand. Proprietary workflows or user preferences will be captured by better memory systems and upkept automatically as one converses with an agent instead of manually updated Skills. 

You might be hearing about how Skills are the hammer and every problem is a nail, maybe there is some truth to that. But who actually has to make hammers at home for all nails they see? If the AI competition keeps forcing Anthropic to innovate in the pace they are, I think its only a matter of time till they realize the above and start pulling all necessary skills to central places and giving their models first class capabilities to load them with the users only seeing they are loaded. The rest will slowly turn to memories and Skills will be a niche thing that is only kept for backwards compatibility.
